Reference-contexts: The sequence fv (n)g is the sequence of polygons v (n) obtained during the simulation, n sweep is the number of sweeps, and n 0 is the length of the burn-in period. The problem we have just stated cannot be solved with ordinary MCMC methods <ref> (e.g. the Metropolis-Hastings algorithm, see Tierney, 1994) </ref>, because the chain must visit spaces of different dimension and switch from one to another. The reversible jump algorithm proposed by Green (1995), gives a solution by suitably modifying the Metropolis-Hastings algorithm to work in general state spaces. <p> Such a chain is positive recurrent; if it is also Harris recurrent the convergence to equilibrium occurs for all starting points <ref> (see Tierney, 1994, for a proof of these assertions) </ref>.
